1
00:00:12,879 --> 00:00:14,847
[THUNDER CRASHING]

2
00:00:27,660 --> 00:00:29,855
DAISY:
Will? Rob?

3
00:00:30,063 --> 00:00:32,497
Stop playing games.

4
00:00:34,534 --> 00:00:36,126
Will?

5
00:00:40,840 --> 00:00:41,829
[GASPS]

6
00:00:44,110 --> 00:00:45,600
Will!

7
00:00:53,653 --> 00:00:55,120
[WILL YELLS THEN GIRLS SCREAM]

8
00:00:55,422 --> 00:00:58,448
[WILL & ROB LAUGHING]

9
00:00:58,658 --> 00:01:02,287
You ass. I hate you.

10
00:01:02,495 --> 00:01:04,019
ROB: Oh, yeah.
We're having fun.

11
00:01:04,230 --> 00:01:05,527
You call this fun?

12
00:01:05,732 --> 00:01:07,359
Welcome to small island living.

13
00:01:07,567 --> 00:01:09,865
Get used to it,
because you are stuck here.

14
00:01:10,070 --> 00:01:11,628
Only until we graduate.

15
00:01:13,406 --> 00:01:14,373
[THUNDER CRASHING]

16
00:01:16,309 --> 00:01:18,743
Can we go now?
The storm is getting worse.

17
00:01:18,945 --> 00:01:20,913
No, that's the point.
It's automatic.

18
00:01:21,114 --> 00:01:25,551
Every time there's an electrical storm in
the area, lightning strikes this graveyard.

19
00:01:25,752 --> 00:01:26,776
It's freaky.

20
00:01:26,986 --> 00:01:29,045
Freaky romantic?
Heh, heh.

21
00:01:29,255 --> 00:01:30,620
Come here.

22
00:01:31,758 --> 00:01:32,782
[GIRLS SCREAM]

23
00:01:37,831 --> 00:01:40,265
ROB:
Ho-ho! There it is.

24
00:01:41,835 --> 00:01:43,826
Oh...
Oh, that's it. I'm out of here.

25
00:01:44,037 --> 00:01:45,231
Me too.

26
00:01:46,606 --> 00:01:49,871
Cracked the old memorial. Creepy.
That's messed up.

27
00:01:52,011 --> 00:01:53,842
What's the old memorial?

28
00:01:54,047 --> 00:01:57,813
Sabbath day suicide? Our urban
legends don't make it to the big city?

29
00:01:58,017 --> 00:02:00,247
Lucky if your mail
makes it to the mainland.

30
00:02:00,453 --> 00:02:02,751
Hey, it's not a legend, you buffoon.

31
00:02:03,423 --> 00:02:04,856
Well?
ROB: Well, years ago,

32
00:02:05,058 --> 00:02:08,425
there was an old priest
who got a bunch of crazies together

33
00:02:08,628 --> 00:02:11,825
who burned themselves to death
in some, like, ritual.

34
00:02:12,031 --> 00:02:14,022
Like the Jonestown cult.
Yes.

35
00:02:14,234 --> 00:02:15,701
Can we go now?

36
00:02:16,703 --> 00:02:19,035
Yeah, yeah. First I gotta
take a leak. Heh.

37
00:02:20,540 --> 00:02:22,531
Don't watch, ladies. Heh.

38
00:02:30,049 --> 00:02:31,038
[ZIPPER ZIPS]

39
00:02:35,889 --> 00:02:38,357
[INDISTINCT WHISPERING]

40
00:03:19,332 --> 00:03:20,560
[EXHALES]

41
00:03:20,767 --> 00:03:21,756
[WHISTLES]

42
00:03:21,968 --> 00:03:23,936
[INDISTINCT OVERLAPPING VOICES]

43
00:03:29,242 --> 00:03:30,732
[GRUNTS]

44
00:03:35,648 --> 00:03:37,206
[GROANS]

45
00:03:39,319 --> 00:03:41,219
<i># Straight #</i>

46
00:03:41,421 --> 00:03:44,083
<i># Is it finding them? ##</i>

47
00:03:45,959 --> 00:03:47,153
[MELISSA MOANING]

48
00:03:47,360 --> 00:03:50,352
[STATIC CRACKLING
OVER EARPHONES]

49
00:03:56,135 --> 00:03:57,261
<i>Aah!
Aah!</i>

50
00:03:57,971 --> 00:04:00,439
What happened, Daisy?
What's going on?

51
00:04:01,107 --> 00:04:02,938
I just saw something on my screen.

52
00:04:05,044 --> 00:04:06,409
Will?

53
00:04:07,213 --> 00:04:08,646
Will?

54
00:04:09,449 --> 00:04:11,542
Daisy's freaking out.
We gotta go.

55
00:04:11,751 --> 00:04:14,652
DAISY: I'm calling him now.
This better not be another joke!

56
00:04:14,854 --> 00:04:17,948
Where are you, Will?

57
00:04:18,157 --> 00:04:21,149
Will.
All right, come on.

58
00:04:22,028 --> 00:04:24,724
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

59
00:04:24,931 --> 00:04:25,920
[GASPS]

60
00:04:28,001 --> 00:04:30,970
[BOTH SCREAMING]

61
00:04:32,672 --> 00:04:36,039
MAN:
All right, Father, give it a try.

62
00:04:36,242 --> 00:04:38,870
And the Lord said, "Let there be light. "

63
00:04:39,078 --> 00:04:41,478
And there was light.
Oh.

64
00:04:41,981 --> 00:04:46,714
And he saw that the light was good.
Well, I don't know how good the light is.

65
00:04:46,919 --> 00:04:49,479
Well, I'm just glad
that they're working again. Heh.

66
00:04:49,689 --> 00:04:52,522
You know, you're truly
a jack-of-all-trades.

67
00:04:52,725 --> 00:04:56,525
Ha-ha-ha. Unfortunately my ex-wife would
tell you I'm a jack of a different kind.

68
00:04:56,729 --> 00:04:57,718
[CELL PHONE RINGS]

69
00:04:57,930 --> 00:04:59,397
Excuse me.

70
00:05:00,500 --> 00:05:02,365
Hello?

71
00:05:02,568 --> 00:05:04,263
Daisy, what's going...?

72
00:05:04,470 --> 00:05:06,768
All right, calm down. Calm...
Calm down.

73
00:05:06,973 --> 00:05:08,702
Where are you?

74
00:05:08,908 --> 00:05:13,902
All right, look, I want you to stay there.
I'm on my way, okay? Stay there. Bye.

75
00:05:14,113 --> 00:05:17,048
MAN:
And that's the last of it.

76
00:05:17,250 --> 00:05:19,684
We bid adieu to you,
Mr. Thunderstorm.

77
00:05:19,886 --> 00:05:22,047
Thanks for the memories.

78
00:05:22,689 --> 00:05:24,680
Really?
What?

79
00:05:25,325 --> 00:05:26,792
It was an attempt at humor.

80
00:05:26,993 --> 00:05:31,589
Sadly, you're not gonna have another
attempt like that for at least another week.

81
00:05:31,798 --> 00:05:32,787
Yeah, I know.

82
00:05:32,999 --> 00:05:35,729
That high-pressure system's gonna
keep things pretty boring around here.

83
00:05:35,935 --> 00:05:37,425
[CELL PHONE RINGS]

84
00:05:40,206 --> 00:05:41,400
Hal?
Yeah, it's me.

85
00:05:41,607 --> 00:05:42,938
Something's up with Daisy.

86
00:05:43,609 --> 00:05:45,099
<i>What happened?
I don't know.</i>

87
00:05:45,311 --> 00:05:48,405
She called me in a panic.
She's at the cemetery.

88
00:05:48,614 --> 00:05:51,014
<i>What's she doing there?
How should I know?</i>

89
00:05:51,217 --> 00:05:54,243
Not my night, it's yours.
You're gonna start with me now?

90
00:05:54,454 --> 00:05:56,752
I'm headed over there
to pick her up now.

91
00:05:56,956 --> 00:05:59,789
Why don't you meet us at the house?
All right.

92
00:06:00,526 --> 00:06:01,720
You okay?

93
00:06:01,928 --> 00:06:03,225
Yeah, I'm fine. Um...

94
00:06:03,429 --> 00:06:06,489
Just get the weather update
to the mainland station.

95
00:06:06,699 --> 00:06:07,893
Thanks, Brett.

96
00:06:08,201 --> 00:06:10,362
[CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING]

97
00:06:14,374 --> 00:06:16,069
Tell me something.

98
00:06:16,809 --> 00:06:19,835
Does that look like the corpse
of a 17-year-old boy to you?

99
00:06:21,147 --> 00:06:23,047
More like 200.

100
00:06:24,050 --> 00:06:25,847
Are you sure this is Will?

101
00:06:26,786 --> 00:06:28,617
That's what they said.

102
00:06:28,821 --> 00:06:30,812
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

103
00:06:31,023 --> 00:06:34,857
Why, you think they exhumed a body?
Kids and their pranks.

104
00:06:35,061 --> 00:06:36,585
We were all 17 once, no?

105
00:06:36,796 --> 00:06:38,923
I don't know, Doug.

106
00:06:39,198 --> 00:06:41,063
Look at their faces.

107
00:06:42,769 --> 00:06:44,430
I don't think it's a prank.

108
00:06:46,005 --> 00:06:49,441
Let's get it over to the morgue,
see if we can get a positive ID, huh?

109
00:06:51,811 --> 00:06:53,745
[SOBS AND SNIFFLES]

110
00:07:08,895 --> 00:07:10,123
Sweetie.

111
00:07:10,930 --> 00:07:12,488
Are you okay?

112
00:07:12,698 --> 00:07:15,326
Will's dead.
What?

113
00:07:17,670 --> 00:07:20,161
Honey, why don't you go inside
and lie down, huh?

114
00:07:23,042 --> 00:07:24,669
[SIGHS]

115
00:07:25,478 --> 00:07:28,504
[WHISPERS] What happened?
We don't know what happened yet.

116
00:07:28,714 --> 00:07:31,182
We said she wasn't gonna
hang out with that kid.

117
00:07:31,384 --> 00:07:34,114
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
No, you said that. She's 17, not 7.

118
00:07:34,320 --> 00:07:35,947
That's not what I meant.

119
00:07:36,956 --> 00:07:40,187
Look, I said the wrong thing. I'm sorry.

120
00:07:43,396 --> 00:07:46,092
Look, it's cold out here.

121
00:07:46,299 --> 00:07:49,268
I'm gonna go see how she's doing.
All right.

122
00:07:49,469 --> 00:07:50,834
Wait, I, um...

123
00:07:52,004 --> 00:07:53,369
I made you a sandwich.

124
00:07:54,540 --> 00:07:55,939
You made me a sandwich?

125
00:07:56,142 --> 00:07:57,905
I figured you'd have a late night.

126
00:07:58,110 --> 00:08:02,012
And I know how you get when you eat
that junk out of the vending machine.

127
00:08:02,882 --> 00:08:05,316
You still like me.
Hey, don't push it.

128
00:08:10,089 --> 00:08:12,057
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

129
00:08:13,993 --> 00:08:15,961
[SOBBING]

130
00:08:16,896 --> 00:08:18,887
[CELL PHONE RINGING]

131
00:08:22,969 --> 00:08:24,061
<i>Will?
WILL: Daisy.</i>

132
00:08:24,270 --> 00:08:25,532
<i>Will?
Help me.</i>

133
00:08:25,738 --> 00:08:27,638
[MAN SCREAMS THEN STATIC
CRACKLING OVER PHONE]

134
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:29,102
[MAN LAUGHING IN DEEP VOICE
OVER PHONE]

135
00:08:29,308 --> 00:08:30,639
Will!

136
00:08:32,945 --> 00:08:33,912
[SCREAMS]

137
00:09:08,548 --> 00:09:12,245
The rate of decomposition
is absolutely staggering.

138
00:09:12,451 --> 00:09:16,182
What could cause this?
The kids said lightning struck the area.

139
00:09:16,389 --> 00:09:18,721
You think he was struck by lightning?

140
00:09:19,592 --> 00:09:21,423
It could answer part of it.

141
00:09:21,627 --> 00:09:25,927
But there's gotta be more, a lot more.

142
00:09:26,132 --> 00:09:28,327
The sheer tissue deterioration.

143
00:09:28,534 --> 00:09:31,298
His internal organs are drained
of all fluids.

144
00:09:31,504 --> 00:09:33,472
[SIGHS]

145
00:09:33,839 --> 00:09:38,503
You've been doing this a long time, doc.
You ever seen anything like this before?

146
00:09:39,278 --> 00:09:41,473
No. Never.

147
00:09:43,182 --> 00:09:47,175
I'm out of my league here. I don't have
the tools for this kind of analysis.

148
00:09:47,386 --> 00:09:50,321
I want to send this body off
to a lab in Seattle.

149
00:09:51,190 --> 00:09:54,751
Hal, Will's father is here to see you.
He seems pretty upset.

150
00:09:54,961 --> 00:09:57,725
Yeah, I'm sure he is.

151
00:10:03,769 --> 00:10:04,793
Carl?

152
00:10:08,741 --> 00:10:10,174
I'm sorry for your loss.

153
00:10:10,376 --> 00:10:13,573
What happened?
We don't know what happened yet.

154
00:10:13,779 --> 00:10:15,371
My boy's dead.

155
00:10:16,315 --> 00:10:19,944
I know he is. Look, it could've
just as easily been my own daughter.

156
00:10:20,152 --> 00:10:23,246
I wanna know just as badly as you do,
and when I find out,

157
00:10:23,456 --> 00:10:25,924
you'll be the first person I call,
I promise.

158
00:10:26,125 --> 00:10:27,786
I want to see him.

159
00:10:30,329 --> 00:10:32,854
It's not a good idea.
I want to see him.

160
00:10:35,568 --> 00:10:38,901
The body is in bad shape.
I wanna see my son.

161
00:10:42,541 --> 00:10:43,769
Okay, come on.

162
00:10:49,849 --> 00:10:51,077
[DOOR OPENS]

163
00:11:02,328 --> 00:11:03,818
What?

164
00:11:04,797 --> 00:11:06,424
What the hell is this?

165
00:11:06,632 --> 00:11:08,862
Where's my boy?
Doc.

166
00:11:09,835 --> 00:11:11,063
What's going on?

167
00:11:11,270 --> 00:11:12,532
I haven't left the room.

168
00:11:13,639 --> 00:11:15,504
Stop lying to me.

169
00:11:15,708 --> 00:11:18,700
We're the only two people
that have been in this room.

170
00:11:18,911 --> 00:11:22,745
I was looking at your boy a minute ago.
This is some kind of sick joke.

171
00:11:41,901 --> 00:11:43,835
[SIGHING]

172
00:11:51,177 --> 00:11:56,308
Just so's you know, I'm packing heat
and I came first in my shooting class.

173
00:11:57,316 --> 00:11:59,284
[INDISTINCT WHISPERING]

174
00:12:04,156 --> 00:12:05,180
Hello?

175
00:12:40,693 --> 00:12:42,422
[WHIMPERING]

176
00:12:44,530 --> 00:12:46,498
[INDISTINCT OVERLAPPING VOICES]

177
00:12:50,236 --> 00:12:53,399
Hal, come in. Something strange
is happening at the cemetery.

178
00:12:53,606 --> 00:12:55,540
Mary, it's Hal. What's going on?

179
00:12:57,576 --> 00:12:58,702
[WHIMPERING]

180
00:13:06,285 --> 00:13:07,343
<i>HAL [OVER RADIO]:
Mary.</i>

181
00:13:07,553 --> 00:13:09,521
[SIREN WAILING]

182
00:13:12,358 --> 00:13:13,347
[HORN HONKING]

183
00:13:17,696 --> 00:13:19,357
Aah...

184
00:13:22,034 --> 00:13:23,092
Mary, do you read me?

185
00:13:23,302 --> 00:13:24,769
Aah!

186
00:13:33,045 --> 00:13:34,512
[SCREAMS]

187
00:13:40,486 --> 00:13:42,386
ASHLEY:
That's a mistake. It can't be.

188
00:13:42,588 --> 00:13:43,782
How big of a drop?

189
00:13:44,423 --> 00:13:48,416
We're at about 870 millibars.

190
00:13:49,361 --> 00:13:52,091
I'd say that's impossible.
We'd have a hurricane.

191
00:13:52,298 --> 00:13:55,062
Yeah, but we don't have a hurricane,
and yet...

192
00:13:55,267 --> 00:13:56,632
[TYPING ON KEYBOARD]

193
00:13:57,136 --> 00:13:58,694
Wait for it.

194
00:13:58,904 --> 00:14:01,168
[BEEPING]

195
00:14:02,575 --> 00:14:04,406
What's that cell over?

196
00:14:04,610 --> 00:14:06,043
[SIGHS]

197
00:14:08,047 --> 00:14:10,015
[BEEPING]

198
00:14:11,584 --> 00:14:15,111
That's the cemetery.
That's where the kids were last night.

199
00:14:15,321 --> 00:14:16,481
What's it at now?

200
00:14:18,190 --> 00:14:22,718
Oh. It's still way too low. Check
the equipment. Gotta be a malfunction.

201
00:14:23,395 --> 00:14:24,987
Well, where you going?

202
00:14:25,731 --> 00:14:27,460
Cemetery.

203
00:14:27,666 --> 00:14:31,227
[SIREN WAILING]

204
00:14:44,183 --> 00:14:47,550
Oh, my God. Doug, take a look at this.

205
00:14:54,326 --> 00:14:56,260
That can't be her, can it?

206
00:14:58,330 --> 00:15:00,457
What the hell is going on around here?

207
00:15:05,271 --> 00:15:08,069
What do you mean, he called you?
I'm telling you.

208
00:15:08,274 --> 00:15:12,210
My phone rang and when I looked at it,
it was Will's number.

209
00:15:12,411 --> 00:15:14,106
Except I have Will's phone.

210
00:15:14,813 --> 00:15:17,782
And then when I answered it,
it was just static.

211
00:15:20,853 --> 00:15:23,048
ROB:
I just can't believe this.

212
00:15:24,089 --> 00:15:27,422
Look, we all saw the lightning
strike the memorial.

213
00:15:27,793 --> 00:15:31,024
Something supernatural is going on
in that cemetery.

214
00:15:32,865 --> 00:15:36,494
What, you think it's a curse
from the Sabbath suicide victims?

215
00:15:36,702 --> 00:15:38,795
I bet Father Telmo knows something.

216
00:15:39,004 --> 00:15:41,165
He knows the history
better than anyone.

217
00:15:41,373 --> 00:15:44,399
We should ask him.
Beats sitting around talking about it.

218
00:15:44,610 --> 00:15:45,838
Meliss?
Me?

219
00:15:46,045 --> 00:15:49,208
Uh, no way. I got enough
bad juju to last a year.

220
00:15:49,415 --> 00:15:52,907
But let me know how it goes, okay?
Okay.

221
00:15:53,385 --> 00:15:55,444
Bye, sweetie.
Bye.

222
00:15:57,923 --> 00:15:59,049
[INDISTINCT WHISPERING]

223
00:15:59,258 --> 00:16:00,350
Hey.

224
00:16:01,894 --> 00:16:03,418
Did you hear that?

225
00:16:04,730 --> 00:16:06,027
No.

226
00:16:21,046 --> 00:16:22,479
Doug.

227
00:16:28,687 --> 00:16:31,019
Did you see that?
DOUG: No.

228
00:16:33,759 --> 00:16:35,420
[CAR APPROACHING]

229
00:16:37,596 --> 00:16:38,585
Great,

230
00:16:38,797 --> 00:16:40,856
just what I need.

231
00:16:45,771 --> 00:16:47,466
What are you doing here?

232
00:16:47,673 --> 00:16:49,140
Nice to see you too.

233
00:16:49,341 --> 00:16:52,367
No, I have a crime scene.
I can't let you go any further.

234
00:16:52,578 --> 00:16:53,943
I brought my equipment
to take a reading.

235
00:16:54,146 --> 00:16:55,579
HAL:
No, not today.

236
00:17:02,054 --> 00:17:03,544
What the hell?

237
00:17:03,756 --> 00:17:05,724
[INDISTINCT WHISPERING]

238
00:17:09,962 --> 00:17:11,987
[GRUNTING]

239
00:17:14,433 --> 00:17:16,094
[DOUG SCREAMS]

240
00:17:16,468 --> 00:17:17,457
Doug!

241
00:17:19,304 --> 00:17:20,293
Doug!

242
00:17:22,107 --> 00:17:24,075
[BOTH GASPING]

243
00:17:25,811 --> 00:17:27,779
[RUMBLING]

244
00:17:32,885 --> 00:17:34,853
[OVERLAPPING VOICES SCREAM]

245
00:18:02,281 --> 00:18:04,078
ROB:
Father Telmo?

246
00:18:06,351 --> 00:18:07,682
Somebody should
be here, no?

247
00:18:07,886 --> 00:18:09,444
Maybe he's in the back office.

248
00:18:09,655 --> 00:18:11,282
Maybe he's doing an exorcism.

249
00:18:11,490 --> 00:18:13,185
Not funny.

250
00:18:17,863 --> 00:18:19,296
[SIREN WAILING]

251
00:18:24,303 --> 00:18:25,702
Carl.
You see this thing?

252
00:18:25,904 --> 00:18:28,372
What the hell is it?
ASHLEY: We don't know what it is.

253
00:18:28,574 --> 00:18:30,701
It came from the graveyard.
The what?

254
00:18:30,909 --> 00:18:34,470
Cells are all down. I need your phone.
Use someone else's.

255
00:18:34,680 --> 00:18:36,978
I'm not asking, Carl. It's an emergency.

256
00:18:41,153 --> 00:18:43,951
Father?
Hello?

257
00:18:44,556 --> 00:18:46,683
Doesn't look like
he's here.

258
00:18:48,594 --> 00:18:50,721
Yeah.
What's up?

259
00:18:57,736 --> 00:18:59,294
[SCREAMS]

260
00:19:00,706 --> 00:19:02,833
Do you know that guy
or something?

261
00:19:04,843 --> 00:19:05,832
Daisy?

262
00:19:06,845 --> 00:19:09,075
That guy was on my phone
last night.

263
00:19:09,515 --> 00:19:11,540
What? What do you mean...?

264
00:19:12,784 --> 00:19:15,981
What are you doing?
Are you gonna steal from a church now?

265
00:19:16,188 --> 00:19:18,281
I'm investigating.

266
00:19:20,959 --> 00:19:22,893
No. No, tomorrow doesn't work.

267
00:19:23,529 --> 00:19:27,898
Hey, this is an emergency. We have
three fatalities here. I need help now.

268
00:19:28,100 --> 00:19:29,067
[SCOFFS]

269
00:19:29,268 --> 00:19:31,566
You have got to be kidding me.

270
00:19:32,271 --> 00:19:35,206
All right, look, just make sure
they get here by morning.

271
00:19:35,941 --> 00:19:38,569
They're not sending anyone?
Bureaucratic garbage.

272
00:19:38,777 --> 00:19:41,211
They can't get a team here
until the morning.

273
00:19:41,413 --> 00:19:43,381
[WIND WHISTLING]

274
00:19:45,117 --> 00:19:47,585
Hal, you better come see this.

275
00:19:51,823 --> 00:19:53,757
[CAR HORNS HONKING]

276
00:19:57,963 --> 00:19:59,954
What the hell are they doing?

277
00:20:00,165 --> 00:20:02,133
[SIRENS WAIL]

278
00:20:02,367 --> 00:20:04,335
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

279
00:20:05,137 --> 00:20:08,732
Hey, everybody, listen up.
You cannot be here. It's not safe.

280
00:20:09,575 --> 00:20:13,978
Authorities will help figure out what's
going on. Until then, you cannot be here.

281
00:20:14,179 --> 00:20:16,477
This area is off limits, so go home.
Come on.

282
00:20:19,151 --> 00:20:21,551
I'll launch my weather balloon
into that cloud.

283
00:20:21,753 --> 00:20:22,777
What? Are you crazy?

284
00:20:22,988 --> 00:20:26,617
After what we just saw? No way.
Until we figure out what's going on,

285
00:20:26,825 --> 00:20:31,091
I won't let anybody in, including you.
What we're seeing defies explanation.

286
00:20:31,296 --> 00:20:34,060
My point exactly.
That's why I won't let you in there.

287
00:20:34,266 --> 00:20:37,667
If my instruments can pick it up,
we can figure out what it is.

288
00:20:37,869 --> 00:20:42,670
Three people have died within a day.
We don't have till tomorrow.

289
00:20:46,578 --> 00:20:48,068
You're right.

290
00:20:48,313 --> 00:20:49,780
Wow.

291
00:20:50,515 --> 00:20:52,176
If you'd said that more often,

292
00:20:52,384 --> 00:20:55,683
we might still be together.
Let's not get carried away.

293
00:20:55,887 --> 00:20:57,855
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

294
00:21:06,798 --> 00:21:08,288
What is that?
A radiosonde.

295
00:21:08,500 --> 00:21:10,331
Measures atmospheric
parameters.

296
00:21:10,535 --> 00:21:14,699
It'll tell us everything we need to know
about this storm's physical properties.

297
00:21:14,906 --> 00:21:17,033
Okay, you can let it go.

298
00:21:30,222 --> 00:21:32,850
[BEEPING]

299
00:21:34,026 --> 00:21:35,015
It's working.

300
00:21:42,634 --> 00:21:44,033
[COMPUTER BEEPING RAPIDLY]

301
00:21:44,236 --> 00:21:46,898
What's happening?
I don't know.

302
00:21:47,339 --> 00:21:49,705
[STATIC CRACKLING]

303
00:21:50,075 --> 00:21:51,064
What's that?

304
00:21:57,215 --> 00:21:58,512
Did you see that?

305
00:22:03,455 --> 00:22:05,252
Ashley, watch out.
Aah!

306
00:22:10,162 --> 00:22:12,323
All right, that's it,
we're out of here.

307
00:22:30,816 --> 00:22:33,444
[THUNDER RUMBLING]

308
00:22:37,923 --> 00:22:40,892
That was fun.
I think I have what I need.

309
00:22:41,093 --> 00:22:43,391
That doesn't look good.
Sure the data is usable?

310
00:22:43,595 --> 00:22:45,460
These things are made
to take a beating.

311
00:22:45,664 --> 00:22:47,996
Great. Let me know
what you find out.

312
00:22:48,200 --> 00:22:50,930
Wait. Where will you be?
Here.

313
00:22:51,136 --> 00:22:53,604
Are you crazy?
We don't know what we're dealing with.

314
00:22:53,805 --> 00:22:56,968
Yeah, I know, but I can't risk
somebody else getting killed.

315
00:22:57,175 --> 00:23:00,440
Post a sign then.
Put your family first.

316
00:23:00,645 --> 00:23:03,842
What kind of father would I be
if I let somebody get killed

317
00:23:04,049 --> 00:23:06,176
while I'm busy protecting
my own skin?

318
00:23:08,620 --> 00:23:11,487
Just go, please.
I'll be fine, all right?

319
00:23:11,690 --> 00:23:13,021
Okay. Be careful.

320
00:23:14,459 --> 00:23:16,154
All right.

321
00:23:29,941 --> 00:23:31,841
Sweetie, I need that computer.

322
00:23:32,043 --> 00:23:33,977
Do you know who this is?

323
00:23:36,615 --> 00:23:39,106
Where did you find that?
At the church.

324
00:23:39,317 --> 00:23:41,444
Do you know who this is?

325
00:23:42,487 --> 00:23:44,284
That's, um...

326
00:23:44,723 --> 00:23:46,623
Father Barrett...

327
00:23:47,092 --> 00:23:49,151
your great-grandfather.

328
00:23:50,529 --> 00:23:52,963
My great-grandfather?

329
00:23:53,398 --> 00:23:55,263
Suicide-massacre Father Barrett?

330
00:23:55,467 --> 00:23:56,729
Now's not the time.

331
00:23:57,769 --> 00:23:59,634
Why don't we wait another 17 years?

332
00:24:00,439 --> 00:24:04,170
He was not a good man, Daisy.
He did unthinkable things.

333
00:24:04,376 --> 00:24:06,310
It's not something that I'm proud of.

334
00:24:06,645 --> 00:24:09,739
I just think it's something
you might have mentioned.

335
00:24:10,315 --> 00:24:13,307
You're right. And I'm sorry.

336
00:24:13,518 --> 00:24:16,146
Now, please, I need to get in there.

337
00:24:20,859 --> 00:24:24,761
<i>WOMAN [ON TV]: You're tuned to Channel 9.
Coming up, gardening experts share their tips.</i>

338
00:24:24,963 --> 00:24:28,421
<i>You'll get the latest information
to grow the best vegetables in...</i>

339
00:24:28,633 --> 00:24:31,158
<i>MAN 1: At the current rates
of expansion, projections...</i>

340
00:24:32,437 --> 00:24:35,736
<i>MAN 2: The sun is going to be
making an effort to peek through...</i>

341
00:24:35,941 --> 00:24:37,533
[STATIC CRACKLING ON TV]

342
00:24:37,742 --> 00:24:41,940
<i>WILL:
Dad, help me.</i>

343
00:24:42,914 --> 00:24:44,108
<i>Help me.</i>

344
00:24:45,217 --> 00:24:46,684
<i>Help me.</i>

345
00:24:46,885 --> 00:24:48,512
<i>Dad.</i>

346
00:24:48,720 --> 00:24:51,280
<i>Help me. Help me.</i>

347
00:24:51,490 --> 00:24:53,924
<i>Dad, help me.</i>

348
00:25:10,609 --> 00:25:11,576
[SCREAMS]

349
00:25:12,143 --> 00:25:12,905
[STATIC CRACKLING OVER RADIO]

350
00:25:13,111 --> 00:25:14,738
Come on.

351
00:25:15,780 --> 00:25:17,680
Come on.

352
00:25:19,351 --> 00:25:21,148
Damn it.

353
00:25:32,197 --> 00:25:36,133
This is so strange.
Humidity's way too low.

354
00:25:36,334 --> 00:25:38,427
Too low to create water vapor.

355
00:25:38,937 --> 00:25:41,235
And it's heating up, not cooling.

356
00:25:42,507 --> 00:25:46,273
That storm can't physically exist.

357
00:25:46,978 --> 00:25:48,946
I'll tell you what doesn't make sense.

358
00:25:49,147 --> 00:25:52,344
I saw my great-grandfather's face
on my phone last night

359
00:25:52,551 --> 00:25:55,042
when the memorial
was struck by lightning.

360
00:25:55,253 --> 00:25:56,914
I saw a ghost, Mom.

361
00:25:59,925 --> 00:26:03,019
I think he's the one that's making
all of this happen.

362
00:26:07,566 --> 00:26:09,329
[STATIC CRACKLING OVER RADIO]

363
00:26:14,239 --> 00:26:15,297
What the hell?

364
00:26:25,450 --> 00:26:27,145
[TIRES SCREECHING]

365
00:26:35,860 --> 00:26:39,352
Okay, Brett, I'm gonna upload the data
so you can see exactly...

366
00:26:40,265 --> 00:26:43,063
Hello? Brett?

367
00:26:46,671 --> 00:26:48,070
[DOGS BARKING]

368
00:27:07,859 --> 00:27:08,848
[SCREAMING]

369
00:27:23,575 --> 00:27:26,408
WOMAN: Those are Ben's shoes.
MAN: Oh, that doesn't look good.

370
00:27:26,611 --> 00:27:28,238
CLAIRE:
I don't understand.

371
00:27:28,446 --> 00:27:30,107
[SIREN WAILS]

372
00:27:30,882 --> 00:27:32,850
[CROWD MURMURING]

373
00:27:46,164 --> 00:27:48,189
Hal, something happened
to Ben.

374
00:27:48,400 --> 00:27:49,958
I mean...

375
00:27:51,469 --> 00:27:52,561
Good God.

376
00:27:52,771 --> 00:27:54,830
It's the devil's work.

377
00:27:55,040 --> 00:27:57,406
All right, Claire, I'll take care of this.

378
00:27:57,842 --> 00:27:59,366
I saw it.
MAN: Huh?

379
00:28:01,079 --> 00:28:02,603
Thomas?

380
00:28:03,148 --> 00:28:05,776
It took ahold of him like a rag doll.

381
00:28:06,418 --> 00:28:07,442
Took hold of him?

382
00:28:07,819 --> 00:28:11,311
It zapped him, Hal.
Like a death ray.

383
00:28:12,757 --> 00:28:15,157
All right, all right.
What exactly did you see?

384
00:28:15,360 --> 00:28:19,091
I saw the wrath of Satan.
It come down the street. It took his soul.

385
00:28:19,297 --> 00:28:22,198
Calm down. There's a logical
explanation to all of this.

386
00:28:22,400 --> 00:28:24,698
There is a logical explanation.

387
00:28:24,903 --> 00:28:28,839
Military testing. Military testing.
It's always military testing.

388
00:28:29,040 --> 00:28:30,940
All right, that's enough. Thank you.

389
00:28:31,142 --> 00:28:32,871
I need you to clear out. Go home.

390
00:28:33,078 --> 00:28:36,309
Tell your friends it's not safe
to be outside. Please, go.

391
00:28:37,348 --> 00:28:39,282
I saw it, Hal.

392
00:29:26,064 --> 00:29:27,395
You got the genny working.

393
00:29:27,599 --> 00:29:31,160
It sort of kicked on by itself
but I'll take the credit.

394
00:29:31,369 --> 00:29:33,599
What happened?
These things aren't cheap.

395
00:29:33,805 --> 00:29:37,366
I know. I hope the data isn't corrupted.
What do you want me to do?

396
00:29:37,575 --> 00:29:41,272
Build a computer model so we can see
where the storm is drawing energy.

397
00:29:41,479 --> 00:29:45,108
Yeah, okay. Well, where you going?
Hal really needs my help.

398
00:29:45,316 --> 00:29:47,341
Okay.
Thanks.

399
00:29:52,924 --> 00:29:54,186
[GRUNTS]

400
00:30:01,966 --> 00:30:04,935
[STATIC CRACKLING
AND BEEPING]

401
00:30:35,200 --> 00:30:37,896
Hal, people are gathering
in the streets.

402
00:30:38,937 --> 00:30:43,203
Sheriff Hal Miller transmitting on the
state emergency channel. Do you read me?

403
00:30:43,942 --> 00:30:47,139
[CHATTERING]

404
00:30:47,745 --> 00:30:49,474
<i>MAN [OVER RADIO]:
I read you, Hal.</i>

405
00:30:49,681 --> 00:30:50,807
Where's my help?

406
00:30:51,015 --> 00:30:53,711
<i>They're on the ferry.
They'll be there soon.</i>

407
00:30:54,185 --> 00:30:55,880
All right, thank you. Out.

408
00:30:56,087 --> 00:30:57,145
CARL:
Hal!

409
00:30:57,522 --> 00:30:59,080
Hal, get out here.

410
00:31:05,697 --> 00:31:08,427
WOMAN: Get out here.
MAN 1: Sheriff?

411
00:31:09,067 --> 00:31:11,592
Sheriff?
MAN 2: Come on, we need to know.

412
00:31:12,003 --> 00:31:14,062
What's going on here,
folks?

413
00:31:15,273 --> 00:31:18,071
Carl, what is this?

414
00:31:18,276 --> 00:31:20,073
We want the truth, Hal.
Yeah.

415
00:31:20,278 --> 00:31:24,009
We have a right to know.
CARL: Something you're not telling us.

416
00:31:24,215 --> 00:31:27,184
HAL: Look, we have no
idea what's going on,

417
00:31:27,385 --> 00:31:30,752
but state investigators are on a ferry
coming here right now.

418
00:31:31,222 --> 00:31:35,181
Until they get here, you all take shelter.
Shelter? Shelter from what?

419
00:31:35,393 --> 00:31:39,090
There's a dangerous atmospheric
phenomenon happening on the island.

420
00:31:39,297 --> 00:31:42,528
She's right about the phenomenon
but it's not atmospheric.

421
00:31:43,902 --> 00:31:45,665
No? Well, then what is it?

422
00:31:46,537 --> 00:31:47,765
Supernatural.

423
00:31:47,972 --> 00:31:49,940
[CROWD CLAMORING]

424
00:31:52,911 --> 00:31:55,436
I need everybody to stay calm
and show no fear.

425
00:31:55,880 --> 00:31:58,440
That's the first rule.
Fear empowers evil spirits.

426
00:31:58,650 --> 00:31:59,947
It makes them stronger.

427
00:32:00,485 --> 00:32:01,884
I'm sorry, who are you?

428
00:32:02,854 --> 00:32:05,846
Greg Goropolis, paranormal investigator.
I'm here to help.

429
00:32:06,958 --> 00:32:11,520
Well, Mr. Goropolis, I don't know
what dinghy you just jumped off of,

430
00:32:11,729 --> 00:32:14,493
but the last thing we need
is an outsider scaring...

431
00:32:14,699 --> 00:32:18,396
This island is exploding with PKE.
You should be scared.

432
00:32:18,603 --> 00:32:20,127
PKE?
Psychokinetic energy.

433
00:32:20,338 --> 00:32:22,533
Dark energy, spiritual energy.

434
00:32:23,141 --> 00:32:24,733
Has it taken a life yet?

435
00:32:24,943 --> 00:32:28,572
Yeah, we've...
We've lost several in the last 24 hours.

436
00:32:29,080 --> 00:32:33,983
I need to see the victims.
We don't have victims. We have ashes.

437
00:32:34,619 --> 00:32:36,712
We don't have a lot of time then,
do we?

438
00:32:37,121 --> 00:32:40,056
Who here has suffered
the biggest loss so far?

439
00:32:40,758 --> 00:32:41,884
My boy, Will.

440
00:32:43,027 --> 00:32:45,860
Has he tried to contact you?
Excuse me?

441
00:32:46,064 --> 00:32:50,626
Contact. Light bulbs popping,
strange phone calls with static.

442
00:32:50,835 --> 00:32:54,703
I don't know. Maybe there was
something on my TV last night.

443
00:32:55,473 --> 00:32:58,408
Damn near scared me half to death.
We'll start there.

444
00:32:58,609 --> 00:33:00,907
Hold on, hold on.

445
00:33:01,112 --> 00:33:04,309
I'm not letting you start anywhere.
Why not?

446
00:33:04,515 --> 00:33:07,780
Because these people are afraid.

447
00:33:07,986 --> 00:33:09,578
They've lost loved ones.

448
00:33:09,787 --> 00:33:13,621
And I don't need you scaring them
with your talk of garlic and holy water.

449
00:33:13,825 --> 00:33:17,784
So you're just gonna sit around and wait
for that help of yours to show up?

450
00:33:17,996 --> 00:33:19,725
Yeah, that's right.

451
00:33:20,398 --> 00:33:21,922
And what if they don't?

452
00:33:25,770 --> 00:33:27,362
Why are you here anyways?

453
00:33:27,705 --> 00:33:30,765
I really can't control it.
I just go where I'm called.

454
00:33:30,975 --> 00:33:34,274
Look, sheriff, I wanna help these people,
same as you.

455
00:33:35,313 --> 00:33:38,908
Give me a chance.
Tell you what, your help arrives,

456
00:33:39,117 --> 00:33:40,448
I disappear.

457
00:33:46,691 --> 00:33:48,989
All right, Mr. Goropolis,

458
00:33:49,994 --> 00:33:51,325
give it a shot.

459
00:33:51,529 --> 00:33:52,553
Thank you, sheriff.

460
00:33:54,332 --> 00:33:56,027
ROB: You lost me in the
"unfinished business" part.

461
00:33:56,234 --> 00:33:59,226
If spirits feel like
they've been wronged in this world,

462
00:33:59,437 --> 00:34:01,997
they resolve it
before passing on to the next.

463
00:34:02,206 --> 00:34:05,198
So?
So if this is about the suicide victims,

464
00:34:05,410 --> 00:34:09,710
then maybe something in the church
archives will help us figure how to stop it.

465
00:34:09,914 --> 00:34:13,350
Where the heck did you hear that from?
The Internet.

466
00:34:30,134 --> 00:34:31,726
So, what is all this stuff?

467
00:34:31,936 --> 00:34:35,565
It's looking for speech patterns
in the storm's electromagnetic waves.

468
00:34:35,773 --> 00:34:39,937
White-noise generator. Opens a window,
allows those on the other side to appear.

469
00:34:40,144 --> 00:34:42,840
It's just a lot of dime-store electronics.

470
00:34:43,047 --> 00:34:46,983
Costs a lot more than a few dimes
but you got the "electronics" part right.

471
00:34:47,185 --> 00:34:50,382
It's basically what a spirit is.
It's an electronic impulse.

472
00:34:51,489 --> 00:34:53,582
You guys just have a rather large one.

473
00:34:53,791 --> 00:34:58,319
What you're saying is
that we have a storm of spirits?

474
00:34:58,663 --> 00:35:01,291
Evil spirits trapped in this world.

475
00:35:01,499 --> 00:35:05,799
The angry souls are the dark energy,
the yin of the storm, so to speak.

476
00:35:06,003 --> 00:35:12,567
But there has to be a yang, a light soul,
a pure soul that they're clinging to.

477
00:35:12,877 --> 00:35:14,845
[STATIC CRACKLING
OVER COMPUTER]

478
00:35:15,980 --> 00:35:17,948
[MAN WHISPERING INDISTINCTLY]

479
00:35:19,016 --> 00:35:20,745
[SCREECH]

480
00:35:20,952 --> 00:35:22,180
What is that?

481
00:35:23,588 --> 00:35:24,577
Over there.

482
00:35:25,523 --> 00:35:27,081
In the car.

483
00:35:37,101 --> 00:35:39,228
Hello? Can you hear us?

484
00:35:39,670 --> 00:35:42,935
[STATIC CRACKLING AND
WAVERING OVER RADIO]

485
00:35:43,841 --> 00:35:46,935
We're here to help you.
Who am I speaking to?

486
00:35:47,145 --> 00:35:48,544
<i>WILL:
Will.</i>

487
00:35:49,614 --> 00:35:51,047
CARL:
Will?

488
00:35:52,817 --> 00:35:55,217
Will? Son, is that you?

489
00:35:55,887 --> 00:35:58,720
<i>It's Will, Dad.</i>

490
00:36:02,160 --> 00:36:04,993
<i>Dad. Dad.</i>

491
00:36:05,763 --> 00:36:07,253
<i>Help me, Dad.</i>

492
00:36:08,666 --> 00:36:10,861
<i>Help me. Dad?</i>

493
00:36:11,402 --> 00:36:12,391
Will.

494
00:36:12,603 --> 00:36:13,968
<i>Dad?</i>

495
00:36:14,338 --> 00:36:15,703
[SCREAMS]

496
00:36:19,477 --> 00:36:21,468
[STATIC CRACKLING]

497
00:36:22,880 --> 00:36:24,905
HAL:
I don't believe this.

498
00:36:31,155 --> 00:36:34,352
All right, how do we stop these things?

